The MFGIC is a stack of seven twin ionization chambers
with Frisch grids. It is housed in a thin-walled
cylindrical detector shell of 200 mm diameter and 520
mm length. The anode and cathode are 50 mum thick
duralumin foils sandwiched between two rings with
inner and outer diameters of 140 and 170 mm, resp.
The gas mixture is composed of 90% argon and 10%
methane. The detector was located with sub-actinide

Neutron fluence measurements were based on the
.Sub-actinide targets plus a natural uranium target,
deposited in the form of uf(4) as a reference target.
The fissile materials were deposited, by thermal
vacuum evaporation, on each side of cathode foils
stretched between the supporting rings. The diameter
of each target was 80-mm. The total fissile mass of
the reference target was measured by alpha-counting,
while the masses of the sub-actinide targets, pure
metals, were determined by weighting. The total masses
